Say more.

00:48:22.440 --> 00:48:24.480
You had other good
ideas in your--

00:48:24.480 --> 00:48:27.840
AUDIENCE: Yeah, we also-- we
talked about some of my ideas

00:48:27.840 --> 00:48:31.378
were looking at
videos, with motion.

00:48:31.378 --> 00:48:32.253
NANCY KANWISHER: Why?

00:48:32.253 --> 00:48:33.000
AUDIENCE: What'd you say?

00:48:33.000 --> 00:48:33.875
NANCY KANWISHER: Why?

00:48:33.875 --> 00:48:38.950
AUDIENCE: Oh, because
when you get a snake,

00:48:38.950 --> 00:48:41.800
it kind of slithers and has
this very distinctive thing,

00:48:41.800 --> 00:48:44.320
that it feels like the
motion is what creeps me

00:48:44.320 --> 00:48:45.490
out when I see a snake.

00:48:45.490 --> 00:48:46.540
NANCY KANWISHER: Totally.

00:48:46.540 --> 00:48:47.170
Me, too.

00:48:47.170 --> 00:48:49.630
AUDIENCE: And if you
have a rigid thing that

00:48:49.630 --> 00:48:53.560
looked like a snake, but it
was just sliding rigidly,

00:48:53.560 --> 00:48:55.338
then it wouldn't
really creep me out.

00:48:55.338 --> 00:48:56.380
NANCY KANWISHER: Exactly.

00:48:56.380 --> 00:48:57.940
This is a key insight, right?

00:48:57.940 --> 00:49:01.120
So think about if we're
interested in how you perceive

00:49:01.120 --> 00:49:04.180
snakes, we want to know not just
how you do it in some weird lab

00:49:04.180 --> 00:49:04.700
environment.

00:49:04.700 --> 00:49:06.070
We want to know how
you'd actually do that.

00:49:06.070 --> 00:49:07.690
The whole reason
to choose snakes

00:49:07.690 --> 00:49:10.360
is it seems like something that
could be biologically relevant.

00:49:10.360 --> 00:49:12.730
There might be special hardware.

00:49:12.730 --> 00:49:15.410
When I'm out hiking and I
see even a curved stick,

00:49:15.410 --> 00:49:17.967
I, like, jump and shriek
before I can censor myself.

00:49:17.967 --> 00:49:18.550
It's horrible.

00:49:18.550 --> 00:49:19.660
I find it very embarrassing.

00:49:19.660 --> 00:49:21.285
It's not consistent
with my self-image.

00:49:21.285 --> 00:49:23.810
But I have no control
over it; it just happens.

00:49:23.810 --> 00:49:25.310
And so I've thought
for a long time,

00:49:25.310 --> 00:49:27.768
there's some damn bit of my
brain that's making me do that,

00:49:27.768 --> 00:49:29.830
and it pisses me off,
and I'm going to find it.

00:49:29.830 --> 00:49:31.288
Well, we looked
and didn't find it.

00:49:31.288 --> 00:49:34.600
But anyway, you go
from those intuitions.

00:49:34.600 --> 00:49:37.037
Often, your own introspections
are very informative,

00:49:37.037 --> 00:49:38.870
and I think your intuition
is exactly right.

00:49:38.870 --> 00:49:41.920
There's a very characteristic
motion that snakes have,

00:49:41.920 --> 00:49:43.690
and it could be
that that's the cue.

00:49:43.690 --> 00:49:46.975
So then, the trick is you have
slithery motion versus what?

00:49:49.628 --> 00:49:50.170
I don't know.

00:49:50.170 --> 00:49:50.670
That's hard.

00:49:50.670 --> 00:49:53.170
What other kinds of
motions could you have?

00:49:53.170 --> 00:49:56.200
AUDIENCE: Right, so you could
have just even rigid motion,

00:49:56.200 --> 00:50:01.320
where it's not slithering,
or it's not changing shape.

00:50:01.320 --> 00:50:03.192
It's just sliding or rotating.

00:50:03.192 --> 00:50:04.150
NANCY KANWISHER: Right.

00:50:04.150 --> 00:50:05.320
Right, exactly.

00:50:05.320 --> 00:50:07.570
Anyway, all those
are all good ideas.

00:50:07.570 --> 00:50:12.850
Good, so what should the
subject do in the scanner?

00:50:12.850 --> 00:50:15.760
Should they lie there
and go dumdy-dumdy-dum?

00:50:15.760 --> 00:50:17.150
Should they do a task?

00:50:17.150 --> 00:50:18.085
If so, what task?

00:50:22.960 --> 00:50:24.580
Oh, if you guys
don't volunteer, I'm

00:50:24.580 --> 00:50:26.860
going to start
calling on people--

00:50:26.860 --> 00:50:29.020
even though, as
the Jenkins study,

00:50:29.020 --> 00:50:32.170
showed it's nearly impossible to
look at these damn photographs

00:50:32.170 --> 00:50:35.290
and figure out who's who.

00:50:35.290 --> 00:50:37.737
David, in the back.

00:50:37.737 --> 00:50:38.320
AUDIENCE: So--

00:50:38.320 --> 00:50:38.890
NANCY KANWISHER: Task.

00:50:38.890 --> 00:50:39.800
Task, or no task?

00:50:39.800 --> 00:50:40.300
What task?

00:50:40.300 --> 00:50:44.920
AUDIENCE: Yes, we talked about
having the subjects find a way

00:50:44.920 --> 00:50:49.270
to indicate that they're paying
attention and not just dozing

00:50:49.270 --> 00:50:49.900
off.

00:50:49.900 --> 00:50:50.858
NANCY KANWISHER: Right.

00:50:50.858 --> 00:50:56.110
AUDIENCE: So one idea was to
have them essentially indicate

00:50:56.110 --> 00:50:59.080
the source, make [INAUDIBLE]
think about a bunch of problems

00:50:59.080 --> 00:51:01.610
like, well, we don't want
them thinking about snakes

00:51:01.610 --> 00:51:02.860
for the entire our experiment.

00:51:02.860 --> 00:51:04.070
So--

00:51:04.070 --> 00:51:05.150
NANCY KANWISHER: Also, if
they're going to tell you

00:51:05.150 --> 00:51:07.370
they're seeing a snake,
maybe by pushing a button,

00:51:07.370 --> 00:51:09.495
then on the snake trails,
they're pushing a button,

00:51:09.495 --> 00:51:11.203
and on the non-snake
trials, they're not.

00:51:11.203 --> 00:51:12.870
AUDIENCE: Well, on
the non-snake trials,

00:51:12.870 --> 00:51:14.330
they would push another button.

00:51:14.330 --> 00:51:15.950
NANCY KANWISHER: Ah, but then
they have two different motor

00:51:15.950 --> 00:51:16.450
responses.

00:51:16.450 --> 00:51:19.460
AUDIENCE: Yeah, so then we would
have them run the experiment

00:51:19.460 --> 00:51:21.203
again, but switch buttons.

00:51:21.203 --> 00:51:22.370
NANCY KANWISHER: Good, good.

00:51:22.370 --> 00:51:24.620
Smart, very nice.

00:51:24.620 --> 00:51:26.390
AUDIENCE: Ideally,
we might just have

00:51:26.390 --> 00:51:30.632
them perform a task that's
completely unrelated to looking

00:51:30.632 --> 00:51:32.090
at snakes or thinking
about snakes,

00:51:32.090 --> 00:51:34.750
just so that they're
not affecting--

00:51:34.750 --> 00:51:36.500
NANCY KANWISHER:
Absolutely, and the point

00:51:36.500 --> 00:51:37.670
you made before is a good one.

00:51:37.670 --> 00:51:39.670
If you're looking for
snakes all the time, maybe

00:51:39.670 --> 00:51:43.147
even if it's apples and dogs,
you're thinking, is it a snake?

00:51:43.147 --> 00:51:43.730
Is it a snake?

00:51:43.730 --> 00:51:46.640
And maybe you're using that
region, and it's a mess, right?

00:51:46.640 --> 00:51:48.860
Absolutely, yeah.

00:51:48.860 --> 00:51:50.527
All right, so this
is a common challenge

00:51:50.527 --> 00:51:52.193
in experimental design,
and these things

00:51:52.193 --> 00:51:53.490
don't have clear right answers.

00:51:53.490 --> 00:51:55.532
What I want you to do is
just see the trade-offs.

00:51:55.532 --> 00:51:58.670
On the one hand, just
passive viewing, lying there,

00:51:58.670 --> 00:51:59.720
is good in a way.

00:51:59.720 --> 00:52:02.420
The things are just
impinging on your sensoria,

00:52:02.420 --> 00:52:03.980
and it's doing
whatever it will do.

00:52:03.980 --> 00:52:06.320
But the downside is subjects
fall asleep and get bored,

00:52:06.320 --> 00:52:07.890
and you don't know
if they're awake.

00:52:07.890 --> 00:52:08.723
So that's a problem.

00:52:11.400 --> 00:52:14.420
OK, but the key thing
is whatever the task is,

00:52:14.420 --> 00:52:17.250
you don't want the task
to engage asymmetrically

00:52:17.250 --> 00:52:19.250
with the stimulus condition,
because then you're

00:52:19.250 --> 00:52:21.830
building in a confound, right?

00:52:21.830 --> 00:52:24.590
So in the group I was in, we
were talking about, well, you

00:52:24.590 --> 00:52:25.640
could have people--

00:52:25.640 --> 00:52:27.590
well, we were talking, actually,
about faces and objects

00:52:27.590 --> 00:52:28.132
in that case.

00:52:28.132 --> 00:52:30.522
So you could have
people name the things,

00:52:30.522 --> 00:52:32.480
but if they're naming
snakes versus non-snakes,

00:52:32.480 --> 00:52:34.230
it's not very good if
they're going snake,

00:52:34.230 --> 00:52:38.220
snake, snake, snake,
snake, dog, toaster, apple.

00:52:38.220 --> 00:52:41.210
One is easier than the
other and more repetitive.

00:52:41.210 --> 00:52:43.730
There are all kinds
of problems there.

00:52:43.730 --> 00:52:45.590
All right, baseline conditions.

00:52:45.590 --> 00:52:47.690
I didn't really say what
a baseline condition was.

00:52:47.690 --> 00:52:49.700
Sorry about that.

00:52:49.700 --> 00:52:52.520
What I meant by a baseline
is different from a control

00:52:52.520 --> 00:52:53.120
condition.

00:52:53.120 --> 00:52:55.400
The control condition
would be like non-snakes

00:52:55.400 --> 00:52:57.620
contrasted with the snakes.

00:52:57.620 --> 00:53:01.040
Baseline tends to be like a
minimalist condition that's

00:53:01.040 --> 00:53:03.710
supposed to turn the brain off.

00:53:03.710 --> 00:53:05.870
Can we turn the brain off?

00:53:05.870 --> 00:53:09.050
No, of course not, but
we can aspire toward it.

00:53:09.050 --> 00:53:11.240
We can go partway out there.

00:53:11.240 --> 00:53:13.760
We can say, OK, if
we're studying vision,

00:53:13.760 --> 00:53:18.950
let's minimize activity in the
visual system as best we can,

00:53:18.950 --> 00:53:19.880
OK?

00:53:19.880 --> 00:53:21.950
So you could just
have a blank screen

00:53:21.950 --> 00:53:23.660
that feels like a
pretty minimal thing.

00:53:23.660 --> 00:53:25.880
You can have people
close their eyes.

00:53:25.880 --> 00:53:27.710
The reason that, in
vision experiments,

00:53:27.710 --> 00:53:30.290
people tend to have fixation,
where there's a tiny dot

00:53:30.290 --> 00:53:33.170
and subjects are supposed
to hold their eyes on it,

00:53:33.170 --> 00:53:36.210
is that in natural- left
of their own devices,

00:53:36.210 --> 00:53:38.810
people move their eyes a
lot-- several times a second.

00:53:38.810 --> 00:53:41.720
And moving your eyes produces
all kinds of activity and lots

00:53:41.720 --> 00:53:42.980
of neurons.

00:53:42.980 --> 00:53:46.370
And so it's a very
active visual thing,

00:53:46.370 --> 00:53:48.120
even if there's
nothing on the screen.

00:53:48.120 --> 00:53:51.440
And so staring at dot is
closer to shutting off

00:53:51.440 --> 00:53:54.710
your visual system, even though
it's not shutting it off.

00:53:54.710 --> 00:53:58.640
OK, so given that most of the
contrasts we've talked about

00:53:58.640 --> 00:54:01.340
are like faces versus
objects or snakes

00:54:01.340 --> 00:54:04.610
versus non-snakes, and all the
activations that I've shown you

00:54:04.610 --> 00:54:09.320
guys are contrast between
an experimental condition

00:54:09.320 --> 00:54:12.753
and a control condition, why
are we bothering with baseline?

00:54:12.753 --> 00:54:14.420
It doesn't even figure
in that contrast.

00:54:17.670 --> 00:54:18.780
Yes, Jimmy?

00:54:18.780 --> 00:54:20.460
AUDIENCE: Well, if
the region is truly

00:54:20.460 --> 00:54:24.770
selective for only snakes,
you could use the baseline as,

00:54:24.770 --> 00:54:27.180
in this sense, like a control,
because you can compare

00:54:27.180 --> 00:54:28.470
the other control to it.

00:54:28.470 --> 00:54:30.450
If it's really
selective for snakes,

00:54:30.450 --> 00:54:33.940
then the non-snake object should
respond in the same as the

00:54:33.940 --> 00:54:34.830
[? minimal. ?]

00:54:34.830 --> 00:54:36.705
NANCY KANWISHER: Awesome,
everybody get that?

00:54:36.705 --> 00:54:38.310
So that was exactly right.

00:54:38.310 --> 00:54:40.760
And this is, I think, a
very interesting point.

00:54:40.760 --> 00:54:42.300
So suppose we have--

00:54:42.300 --> 00:54:44.440
remember, with MRI, you
just have two numbers.

00:54:44.440 --> 00:54:47.580
So here's the snake
response, and here's

00:54:47.580 --> 00:54:50.170
the non-snake response.

00:54:50.170 --> 00:54:52.770
If we don't have a baseline,
that's all we have--

00:54:52.770 --> 00:54:55.920
two numbers, OK?

00:54:55.920 --> 00:54:57.150
And that's fine.

00:54:57.150 --> 00:55:00.400
If we run enough subjects,
that could be significant.

00:55:00.400 --> 00:55:03.570
But now, let's think what else
we know if we have a baseline.

00:55:03.570 --> 00:55:06.510
Suppose we have a baseline
of staring at dot.

00:55:06.510 --> 00:55:09.038
And that's down here.

00:55:09.038 --> 00:55:10.080
We'll call that fixation.

00:55:13.040 --> 00:55:13.790
Are you impressed?

00:55:13.790 --> 00:55:15.498
And you've run enough
subjects, so that's

00:55:15.498 --> 00:55:16.760
significantly different.

00:55:16.760 --> 00:55:17.660
Are you impressed?

00:55:23.970 --> 00:55:24.470
Yeah.

00:55:24.470 --> 00:55:27.110
AUDIENCE: Less so than if
the fixation were higher up.

00:55:27.110 --> 00:55:28.760
NANCY KANWISHER: Exactly!

00:55:28.760 --> 00:55:29.870
Why?

00:55:29.870 --> 00:55:32.720
AUDIENCE: Because then, if
the results are higher up--

00:55:32.720 --> 00:55:35.840
or if the fixation is the
second one that you just drew--

00:55:35.840 --> 00:55:39.418
then the response to a snake
is twice as much as non-snake.

00:55:39.418 --> 00:55:40.460
NANCY KANWISHER: Exactly.

00:55:40.460 --> 00:55:42.835
Does everybody see how-- yeah,
that might be significant,

00:55:42.835 --> 00:55:44.090
but who cares, right?

00:55:44.090 --> 00:55:47.150
Some tiny little
ratty-ass effect,

00:55:47.150 --> 00:55:51.830
versus if it's like
here, or even--

00:55:51.830 --> 00:55:54.680
this is the case Jimmy was
talking about, like that.

00:55:54.680 --> 00:55:57.290
No response at all
more than staring at a

00:55:57.290 --> 00:56:01.237
dot to the non-snakes, and yet
this response to the snakes.

00:56:01.237 --> 00:56:02.570
That would even more impressive.

00:56:02.570 --> 00:56:05.990
So there are different
degrees of selectivity, right?

00:56:05.990 --> 00:56:07.970
Not just does it
respond differentially,

00:56:07.970 --> 00:56:09.740
but how selective is it?

00:56:09.740 --> 00:56:11.210
Oh, boy, I'm going
way over time.

00:56:11.210 --> 00:56:13.370
I'm sorry.

00:56:13.370 --> 00:56:17.127
So you guys did great
thinking through these things.

00:56:17.127 --> 00:56:19.460
And, of course, I didn't get
